{"title_page": "Periorbital dark circles", "text_new": "{{redirect|Dark circle}}\n\n\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n|\n===Medications===\nAny medications that cause blood vessels to [[vasodilation|dilate]] can cause circles under the eyes to darken. Because the skin under the eyes is very delicate, any increased blood flow shows through the skin.\n\n=\n===Age===\nDark circles are likely to become more noticeable and permanent with age. This is because as people get older, their skin loses [[collagen]], becoming thinner and more translucent. Circles may also gradually begin to appear darker in one eye than the other as a result of some habitual facial expressions, such as an uneven smile.{{citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\n===Sun exposure===\nPrompts your body to produce more melanin, the pigment that gives skin its color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/symptoms/dark-circles-under-eyes/basics/definition/sym-20050624|title=Dark circles under eyes Causes|website=Mayo Clinic|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n===Periorbital hyperpigmentation===\n{{Main article|Periorbital hyperpigmentation}}\n''Periorbital hyperpigmentation'' is the official name for when there is more [[melanin]] produced around the eyes than is usual, giving them a darker color.\n\n==Treatment==\nAt one time, [[hydroquinone]] solution was often mixed in an oil-free moisturizer that acted like a skin bleach. However the use of hydroquinone for skin whitening\nModern treatments include topical creams that are marketed for the condition (e.g. [[L'Oreal]], [[Olay]], Skin Doctors etc.). Various ingredients have been researched, developed and included in these creams. For example, recently, chemical compounds called [[alpha hydroxy acids]] (AHAs) have been added as a beneficial ingredient to creams for dark circles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmeticsinfo.org/alpha-hydroxy-acids|title=Alpha Hydroxy Acids|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref> Specialist treatments including [[laser surgery|laser]] and [[intense pulsed light]] skin surgery can also be used.treatments. [[Low-level laser therapy]], [[autologous]] fat transplantation and [[hyaluronic acid]] fillers are also alternative treatment options.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Alsaad |first1=SM |last2=Mikhail |first2=M |title=Periocular hyperpigmentation: a review of etiology and current treatment options. |journal=Journal of Drugs in Dermatology : JDD |date=February 2013 |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=154\u20137 |pmid=23377386}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Periorbital puffiness]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Dark circle}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Periorbital dark circles\n| synonyms        = Dark circles, infraorbital venous stasis, periorbital hyperpigmentation\n| background      = \n| image           = Dark circles (cropped).png\n| caption         = Minor dark circles and a hint of [[periorbital puffiness]]\u2014a combination principally suggestive of minor [[sleep deprivation]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Sleep medicine]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Periorbital dark circles''' are dark blemishes around the [[human eye|eye]]s. There are many causes of this symptom, including [[heredity]] and [[bruising]].<ref name=\"pmid12838159\">{{cite journal |title=What causes the dark circles that sometimes appear under my eyes? |journal=Mayo Clinic Women's Healthsource |volume=7 |issue=6 |pages=8 |year=2003 |pmid=12838159}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\n\n===Allergies, asthma, and eczema===\nAny condition that causes the eyes to itch can contribute to darker circles due to rubbing or scratching the skin around them. [[Hay fever]] sufferers in particular will notice under-eye \"smudges\" during the height of the allergy season.\n\n===Medications===\nAny medications that cause blood vessels to [[vasodilation|dilate]] can cause circles under the eyes to darken. Because the skin under the eyes is very delicate, any increased blood flow shows through the skin.\n\n===Anemia===\nThe lack of nutrients in the diet, or the lack of a balanced diet, can contribute to the discoloration of the area under the eyes. It is believed that [[iron deficiency]] can cause dark circles as well. Iron deficiency is the most common type of [[anemia]] and this condition is a sign that not enough oxygen is getting to the body tissues.\n\nThe skin can also become more pale during [[pregnancy]] and [[menstruation]] (due to lack of iron), allowing the underlying veins under the eyes to become more visible.\n\n===Fatigue===\nA [[Sleep deprivation|lack of sleep]] and [[Fatigue (medical)|mental fatigue]] can cause paleness of the skin, allowing the blood underneath the skin to become more visible and appear more blue or darker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medicinenet.com/dark_circles_under_the_eyes/symptoms.htm|title=Dark Circles Under the Eyes|last=|first=|date=2012-06-03|website=Medicine.net|publisher=Medicine.net|access-date=2016-04-27}}</ref>\n\n===Age===\nDark circles are likely to become more noticeable and permanent with age. This is because as people get older, their skin loses [[collagen]], becoming thinner and more translucent. Circles may also gradually begin to appear darker in one eye than the other as a result of some habitual facial expressions, such as an uneven smile.{{citation needed|date=February 2010}}\n\n===Sun exposure===\nPrompts your body to produce more melanin, the pigment that gives skin its color.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/symptoms/dark-circles-under-eyes/basics/definition/sym-20050624|title=Dark circles under eyes Causes|website=Mayo Clinic|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n===Periorbital hyperpigmentation===\n{{Main article|Periorbital hyperpigmentation}}\n''Periorbital hyperpigmentation'' is the official name for when there is more [[melanin]] produced around the eyes than is usual, giving them a darker color.\n\n==Treatment==\nAt one time, [[hydroquinone]] solution was often mixed in an oil-free moisturizer that acted like a skin bleach. However the use of hydroquinone for skin whitening has been banned in European countries due to health concerns.  In 2006, the United States [[Food and Drug Administration]] revoked its approval of hydroquinone for over the counter preparations warning that it may cause cancer or have many other detrimental effects.\n\nThe use of hydroquinone skin-whitening products can be toxic, harmful or lethal for humans.\n\nModern treatments include topical creams that are marketed for the condition (e.g. [[L'Oreal]], [[Olay]], Skin Doctors etc.). Various ingredients have been researched, developed and included in these creams. For example, recently, chemical compounds called [[alpha hydroxy acids]] (AHAs) have been added as a beneficial ingredient to creams for dark circles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmeticsinfo.org/alpha-hydroxy-acids|title=Alpha Hydroxy Acids|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref> Specialist treatments including [[laser surgery|laser]] and [[intense pulsed light]] skin surgery can also be used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.docshop.com/education/dermatology/skin-flaws/undereye-circles|title=Undereye Circles|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref> A compounding cream of ''[[Pfaffia paniculata]]'', ''[[Ptychopetalum olacoides]]'' and ''[[Lilium candidum]]'' has also been reported as an effective treatments. [[Low-level laser therapy]], [[autologous]] fat transplantation and [[hyaluronic acid]] fillers are also alternative treatment options.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Alsaad |first1=SM |last2=Mikhail |first2=M |title=Periocular hyperpigmentation: a review of etiology and current treatment options. |journal=Journal of Drugs in Dermatology : JDD |date=February 2013 |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=154\u20137 |pmid=23377386}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Periorbital puffiness]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eye Circles}}\n[[Category:Diseases of the eye and adnexa]]\n[[Category:Symptoms]]\n[[Category:Periorbital conditions]]\n", "name_user": "84.1.50.84", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periorbital_dark_circles"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Nicholas Churton", "text_new": "{{in use}}\nIn March 2017, '''Nicolas Churton''' was murdered at his home in Wrexham by Jordan James Lee Davidson. The case resulted in three Independent Police Complaints Commission investigations. \n\n<br />\n== Nicolas Churton ==\n\nNicolas Churton, aged  67 years old, lived alone at Crescent Close, [[Wrexham]]<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.north-wales.police.uk/news-and-appeals/appeal-for-information-wrexham-murder|title=Appeal for information - Wrexham murder - News and Appeals - North Wales Police|website=www.north-wales.police.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  He was a retired restaurateur who ran restaurants in [[Rossett]], Wrexham and [[Tarporley]], Cheshire<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-42249922|title=Machete killer gets 23 years in jail|date=2017-12-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[North Wales Police]] described him as vulnerable and partly disabled.<ref name=\":6\" />. <br />\n== Events prior to the murder ==\n\nJordan James Lee Davidson, a 25 years old male, committed the murder.<ref name=\":6\" /> In December 2016, he was released from [[HM Prison Parc|HM Parc prison]] on [[Release on licence|license]]. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/iopc-calls-better-information-sharing-following-investigation-north-wales-police-contact-jordan|title=IOPC calls for better information sharing following investigation into North Wales Police contact with Jordan Davidson|last=|first=|date=2019-11-28|website=The Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Afterwards, North Wales Police dealt with him on eight occasions before the [[murder]] of  Nicolas Churton. <ref name=\":3\" />\n\n* 4 December 2016 \u2013 A theft to which he pleaded guilty in court.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*31 January 2017 \u2013 He reported being assaulted.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 14 February 2017 \u2013 An allegation of sexual assault, but he was not charged due to  insufficient evidence.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 1 March 2017 - A theft to which he pleaded guilty in court.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 8 March 2017 \u2013 A report from a member of the public that there was an unknown male inside her vehicle. Jordan Davidson was identified as a suspect but was not charged.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* March 2017 \u2013 A report by Jordan Davidson's landlord that he was bringing stolen property back to the address and that he wished him to leave. <ref name=\":3\" />\n* 13 March 2017 - Arrested for breach of the peace, but later released.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 19 March 2017 \u2013 Arrest for possession of a bladed article in a public place, and released on police bail.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn the 14 March 2017, Nicholas Churton reported a robbery at his home address in Wrexham that had happened two days previously (12 March 2017). <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/ipcc-investigating-prior-police-contact-murder-victim-nicholas-churton|title=IPCC investigating prior police contact with murder victim Nicholas Churton|last=|first=|date=2017-12-06|website=Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> He alleged that a person called Jordan had threatened him with a hammer and stolen a set of keys after he had let him into his home to use the toilet.<ref name=\":0\" />  On the 21 March, Nicolas Churton was spoken to by North Wales Police Officers, who asked him to take steps to help identify Jordan<ref name=\":0\" />  On the 23 March, he told them that Jordan Davidson was the offender.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Murder ==\n\nNicolas Churton was murdered sometime between 23 March and 24 March 2017.<ref name=\":6\" />  At 08.23 am on 27 March 2017, he was found dead at his home.<ref name=\":6\" /> He had been attacked with a machete and a hammer.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/wrexham-murderer-to-spend-longer-behind-bars|title=Wrexham murderer to spend longer behind bars|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The murder investigation was led by Detective Superintendent  Iestyn Davies, North Wales Police.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Post-murder offences ==\n\nJordan Davidson, the day after the murder, committed a further robbery of an elderly male at his home with the same machete he used in the murder. A few days later, he attacked a 53 year old male with a hammer fracturing his skull.<ref name=\":5\" />  While being arrested for murder and other offences, he attacked two police officers, PC Rhys Rushby and PC David Hall with a hammer.<ref name=\":5\" />  Subsequently, both police officers were nominated to attend  the National Police Bravery Awards 2019.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-04-11/debates/F7AC7D0B-A0B7-49F7-99DD-59634265AE99/PoliceComplaintsAndAccountability?highlight=churton#contribution-12F076FA-0588-4A18-B12E-AE964B7F0EA9|title=Police Complaints and Accountability - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  He also assaulted another police officer during his interview for murder<ref name=\":5\" />. While on remand he slashed a prison officer\u2019s neck with a makeshift knife.<ref name=\":5\" /><br />\n\n== Court cases ==\n\nOn  30 November  2017, Jordan Davidson admitted the murder of Nicolas Churton and twelve other offences at the Mold Crown Court.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was sentenced to a minimum of 23 years and four months imprisonment.<ref name=\":0\" />  Subsequently, [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor Genera]]<nowiki/>l [[Robert Buckland]] QC MP argued that Jordan Davidson\u2019s original sentence was too low, referred it to the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]], and the sentence was increased to a minimum of 30 years imprisonment.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) investigations ==\n\nIn April 2017, the North Wales Police self-referred the incident to the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] for investigation (IPCC) <ref name=\":0\" /> On 6 December 2017, the IPCC reported that four police officers and one civilian staff member were being investigated for criminal offences due to the incidents.<ref name=\":0\" />  On 30 May 2018, the IPCC reported that it had started a second investigation into the circumstance behind the murder of Nicholas Churton. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/second-investigation-north-wales-police-linked-murder-nicholas-churton|title=Second investigation into North Wales Police linked to murder of Nicholas Churton|last=|first=|date=2018-05-30|website=Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The focus of that investigation was the management of Jordan Davidson between his release from Parc prison in December 2016 on licence and the murder.<ref name=\":1\" /> The scope of the investigation was the compliance of North Wales Police with both theirs and national policies on post-release offender management .<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n\nOn the 31 October 2018, the IPCC reported that it had concluded the first investigation into the murder. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/learning-and-disciplinary-proceedings-north-wales-police-following-investigation-contact|title=Learning and disciplinary proceedings for North Wales Police following investigation into contact with Nicholas Churton|last=|first=|date=2018-10-31|website=Independent Police Complaints Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The IPCC mentioned several issues about the investigation into the Robbery reported by Nicolas Churton. <ref name=\":2\" /> The police officers that spoke to him had recorded the complaint as [[theft]] ,rather than as [[robbery]], and that influenced the threat and risk assessment of the incident. <ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, the vulnerability of him was incorrectly assessed.<ref name=\":2\" /> Furthermore, the details of the person who was able to identify Jordan Davidson as the offender for the robbery were not recorded.<ref name=\":2\" /> The IPCC stated that some police officers were identified as potentially committing police disciplinary offences. <ref name=\":2\" />    A police sergeant and acting police Inspector were dealt with for unsatisfactory supervision of their staff.<ref name=\":2\" />  A further two police officers appeared at a misconduct meeting held by North Wales Police, at which they were found not to have committed misconduct, but were dealt with for unsatisfactory performance.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n\nOn the 28 November 2019, The IPCC reported the result of its second investigation of the case. <ref name=\":3\" /> It called for North Wales Police, the [[National Probation Service]], and [[Community Rehabilitation Company]] to improve their procedures for sharing information.<ref name=\":3\" />  The IPCC investigation found that Jordan Davidson was dealt with by the North Wales police on eight occasions between his release from Parc Prison and the murder of Nicolas Churton<ref name=\":3\" />   Due to procedural issues there was insufficient information shared between North Wales Police and the Probation Service.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, the North Wales police service has not breached any national policies<ref name=\":3\" /> The  reason was at the time Jordan Davidson was released from Parc prison, he had not committed any sexual or violent offences. <ref name=\":3\" /> Therefore, he was not categorised as a high risk offender that needed supervision as a category one or two [[Multi-Agency Public Protection Arrangement|Multi-Agency Public Protection Arrangements]] (MAPPA) offender.<ref name=\":3\" />  It was not within the remit of the IPCC to investigate the Probation service or Community Rehabilitation Company.<ref name=\":3\" /> As a result of the second investigation a further police sergeant was referred to the the North Wales Police for consideration of a misconduct hearing.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Parliamentary debate ==\n[[File:Ian Lucas.jpg|thumb|Ian Lucas]]\n\nOn the 11 April 2019, [[Ian Lucas]], Member of Parliament for Wrexham secured an [[adjournment debate]] in the [[House of Commons]] about the murder of Nicolas Churton.  He stated that he had discovered about the errors in the case from Jez Hemming, a report for the [[Daily Post (North Wales)|Daily Post]]. He accused North Wales police, the probation service, the community rehabilitation company, the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]], and the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] of hiding the mistakes.  He further alleged that Mark Polin, the Chief Constable for North Wales Police had misled him about the case. [[Nick Hurd]], the Minister for Policing and the fire service replied on behalf of the Government. He acknowledged their were procedure failures that contributed to the murder. However,  Rory Stewart, the Minister of Justice had already provided Ian Lucas reassurance that any issues about the case had been addressed and there was no need for an inquiry into it. <ref name=\":4\" />   On 26 June 2018, there was a further Parliamentary debate titled 'North Wales Police and Nicholas Churton' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-06-26/debates/48A3C0A0-19E4-4A7E-AB9E-0F75EAE8B9BB/NorthWalesPoliceAndNicholasChurton?highlight=churton#contribution-155E5433-DFA9-4171-870D-FDE6C9952790|title=North Wales Police and Nicholas Churton - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. On 12 March 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-03-12/debates/4F8DA548-29D7-4652-99F6-A6BB6C5E0EAE/ProbationReforms?highlight=churton#contribution-EB44FDF8-CB79-4CA6-A6BB-F5DC05664B73|title=Probation Reforms - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and 14 May 2019 there were further mentions about the case in the House of Commons<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-05-14/debates/1F4E18A1-F260-4F82-888D-59FEDD63E3C5/PrisonsAndProbation?highlight=churton#contribution-8B2B9B78-B6EF-40D2-A79E-1AE431F64E5E|title=Prisons and Probation - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Member of Parliament accusations of being mislead ==\n\nThe IPCC completed a separate investigation into the complaints made by Ian Lucas, the Member of Parliament for Wrexham, that he was misled by  Mark Polin, the Chief Constable of North Wales Police. The IPCC reported that it had found no evidence he had been deliberately misled.<ref name=\":3\" />  In November 2019, Ian Lucas stated that he disagreed with the IPCC findings, and consequently, [[Arfon Jones]], the North Wales [[Police and crime commissioner|Police Crime Commissioner]], said he was \"pursuing a personal vendetta against the former chief constable and impugning his integrity with such distasteful relish\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leaderlive.co.uk/news/18039278.police-boss-ex-wrexham-mp-row-findings-investigation-former-chief-constable/|title=Police boss and ex-Wrexham MP row over findings of investigation into former chief constable|website=The Leader|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/df81f997-1c62-4aeb-92d0-e0063c3d972c?in=17:03:11 House of Commons  Adjournment Debate 11 April 2019 -Parlimentlive.TV]\n\n[https://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/shows/murdertown/articles/murdertown-s2-episodes Murdertown Wrexham - Series 2, Episode 2 Crime+Investigation TV channel]\n\n[https://www.channel4.com/news/police-accused-of-concealing-errors-that-could-have-prevented-murder 'Police accused of \u2018concealing errors\u2019 that could have prevented murder' - Channel 4 Documentary on the Case]\n\n[https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/wrexham-murder-victim-lovely-man-12811510 Video footage of police officers at the murder scene]\n", "text_old": "{{under construction}}\nIn March 2017, '''Nicolas Churton''' was murdered at his home in Wrexham by Jordan James Lee Davidson. The case resulted in three Independent Police Complaints Commission investigations. \n\n<br />\n== Nicolas Churton ==\n\nNicolas Churton, aged  67 years old, lived alone at Crescent Close, [[Wrexham]]<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.north-wales.police.uk/news-and-appeals/appeal-for-information-wrexham-murder|title=Appeal for information - Wrexham murder - News and Appeals - North Wales Police|website=www.north-wales.police.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  He was a retired restaurateur who ran restaurants in [[Rossett]], Wrexham and [[Tarporley]], Cheshire<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-42249922|title=Machete killer gets 23 years in jail|date=2017-12-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[North Wales Police]] described him as vulnerable and partly disabled.<ref name=\":6\" />. <br />\n== Events prior to the murder ==\n\nJordan James Lee Davidson, a 25 years old male, committed the murder.<ref name=\":6\" /> In December 2016, he was released from [[HM Prison Parc|HM Parc prison]] on [[Release on licence|license]]. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/iopc-calls-better-information-sharing-following-investigation-north-wales-police-contact-jordan|title=IOPC calls for better information sharing following investigation into North Wales Police contact with Jordan Davidson|last=|first=|date=2019-11-28|website=The Independent Office for Police Conduct (IOPC)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Afterwards, North Wales Police dealt with him on eight occasions before the [[murder]] of  Nicolas Churton. <ref name=\":3\" />\n\n* 4 December 2016 \u2013 A theft to which he pleaded guilty in court.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*31 January 2017 \u2013 He reported being assaulted.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 14 February 2017 \u2013 An allegation of sexual assault, but he was not charged due to  insufficient evidence.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 1 March 2017 - A theft to which he pleaded guilty in court.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 8 March 2017 \u2013 A report from a member of the public that there was an unknown male inside her vehicle. Jordan Davidson was identified as a suspect but was not charged.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* March 2017 \u2013 A report by Jordan Davidson's landlord that he was bringing stolen property back to the address and that he wished him to leave. <ref name=\":3\" />\n* 13 March 2017 - Arrested for breach of the peace, but later released.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* 19 March 2017 \u2013 Arrest for possession of a bladed article in a public place, and released on police bail.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOn the 14 March 2017, Nicholas Churton reported a robbery at his home address in Wrexham that had happened two days previously (12 March 2017). <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/ipcc-investigating-prior-police-contact-murder-victim-nicholas-churton|title=IPCC investigating prior police contact with murder victim Nicholas Churton|last=|first=|date=2017-12-06|website=Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> He alleged that a person called Jordan had threatened him with a hammer and stolen a set of keys after he had let him into his home to use the toilet.<ref name=\":0\" />  On the 21 March, Nicolas Churton was spoken to by North Wales Police Officers, who asked him to take steps to help identify Jordan<ref name=\":0\" />  On the 23 March, he told them that Jordan Davidson was the offender.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Murder ==\n\nNicolas Churton was murdered sometime between 23 March and 24 March 2017.<ref name=\":6\" />  At 08.23 am on 27 March 2017, he was found dead at his home.<ref name=\":6\" /> He had been attacked with a machete and a hammer.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/wrexham-murderer-to-spend-longer-behind-bars|title=Wrexham murderer to spend longer behind bars|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The murder investigation was led by Detective Superintendent  Iestyn Davies, North Wales Police.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Post-murder offences ==\n\nJordan Davidson, the day after the murder, committed a further robbery of an elderly male at his home with the same machete he used in the murder. A few days later, he attacked a 53 year old male with a hammer fracturing his skull.<ref name=\":5\" />  While being arrested for murder and other offences, he attacked two police officers, PC Rhys Rushby and PC David Hall with a hammer.<ref name=\":5\" />  Subsequently, both police officers were nominated to attend  the National Police Bravery Awards 2019.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-04-11/debates/F7AC7D0B-A0B7-49F7-99DD-59634265AE99/PoliceComplaintsAndAccountability?highlight=churton#contribution-12F076FA-0588-4A18-B12E-AE964B7F0EA9|title=Police Complaints and Accountability - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  He also assaulted another police officer during his interview for murder<ref name=\":5\" />. While on remand he slashed a prison officer\u2019s neck with a makeshift knife.<ref name=\":5\" /><br />\n\n== Court cases ==\n\nOn  30 November  2017, Jordan Davidson admitted the murder of Nicolas Churton and twelve other offences at the Mold Crown Court.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was sentenced to a minimum of 23 years and four months imprisonment.<ref name=\":0\" />  Subsequently, [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor Genera]]<nowiki/>l [[Robert Buckland]] QC MP argued that Jordan Davidson\u2019s original sentence was too low, referred it to the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]], and the sentence was increased to a minimum of 30 years imprisonment.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) investigations ==\n\nIn April 2017, the North Wales Police self-referred the incident to the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] for investigation (IPCC) <ref name=\":0\" /> On 6 December 2017, the IPCC reported that four police officers and one civilian staff member were being investigated for criminal offences due to the incidents.<ref name=\":0\" />  On 30 May 2018, the IPCC reported that it had started a second investigation into the circumstance behind the murder of Nicholas Churton. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/second-investigation-north-wales-police-linked-murder-nicholas-churton|title=Second investigation into North Wales Police linked to murder of Nicholas Churton|last=|first=|date=2018-05-30|website=Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The focus of that investigation was the management of Jordan Davidson between his release from Parc prison in December 2016 on licence and the murder.<ref name=\":1\" /> The scope of the investigation was the compliance of North Wales Police with both theirs and national policies on post-release offender management .<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n\nOn the 31 October 2018, the IPCC reported that it had concluded the first investigation into the murder. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.policeconduct.gov.uk/news/learning-and-disciplinary-proceedings-north-wales-police-following-investigation-contact|title=Learning and disciplinary proceedings for North Wales Police following investigation into contact with Nicholas Churton|last=|first=|date=2018-10-31|website=Independent Police Complaints Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The IPCC mentioned several issues about the investigation into the Robbery reported by Nicolas Churton. <ref name=\":2\" /> The police officers that spoke to him had recorded the complaint as [[theft]] ,rather than as [[robbery]], and that influenced the threat and risk assessment of the incident. <ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, the vulnerability of him was incorrectly assessed.<ref name=\":2\" /> Furthermore, the details of the person who was able to identify Jordan Davidson as the offender for the robbery were not recorded.<ref name=\":2\" /> The IPCC stated that some police officers were identified as potentially committing police disciplinary offences. <ref name=\":2\" />    A police sergeant and acting police Inspector were dealt with for unsatisfactory supervision of their staff.<ref name=\":2\" />  A further two police officers appeared at a misconduct meeting held by North Wales Police, at which they were found not to have committed misconduct, but were dealt with for unsatisfactory performance.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n\nOn the 28 November 2019, The IPCC reported the result of its second investigation of the case. <ref name=\":3\" /> It called for North Wales Police, the [[National Probation Service]], and [[Community Rehabilitation Company]] to improve their procedures for sharing information.<ref name=\":3\" />  The IPCC investigation found that Jordan Davidson was dealt with by the North Wales police on eight occasions between his release from Parc Prison and the murder of Nicolas Churton<ref name=\":3\" />   Due to procedural issues there was insufficient information shared between North Wales Police and the Probation Service.<ref name=\":3\" /> However, the North Wales police service has not breached any national policies<ref name=\":3\" /> The  reason was at the time Jordan Davidson was released from Parc prison, he had not committed any sexual or violent offences. <ref name=\":3\" /> Therefore, he was not categorised as a high risk offender that needed supervision as a category one or two [[Multi-Agency Public Protection Arrangement|Multi-Agency Public Protection Arrangements]] (MAPPA) offender.<ref name=\":3\" />  It was not within the remit of the IPCC to investigate the Probation service or Community Rehabilitation Company.<ref name=\":3\" /> As a result of the second investigation a further police sergeant was referred to the the North Wales Police for consideration of a misconduct hearing.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Parliamentary debate ==\n[[File:Ian Lucas.jpg|thumb|Ian Lucas]]\n\nOn the 11 April 2019, [[Ian Lucas]], Member of Parliament for Wrexham secured an [[adjournment debate]] in the [[House of Commons]] about the murder of Nicolas Churton.  He stated that he had discovered about the errors in the case from Jez Hemming, a report for the [[Daily Post (North Wales)|Daily Post]]. He accused North Wales police, the probation service, the community rehabilitation company, the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]], and the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] of hiding the mistakes.  He further alleged that Mark Polin, the Chief Constable for North Wales Police had misled him about the case. [[Nick Hurd]], the Minister for Policing and the fire service replied on behalf of the Government. He acknowledged their were procedure failures that contributed to the murder. However,  Rory Stewart, the Minister of Justice had already provided Ian Lucas reassurance that any issues about the case had been addressed and there was no need for an inquiry into it. <ref name=\":4\" />   On 26 June 2018, there was a further Parliamentary debate titled 'North Wales Police and Nicholas Churton' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-06-26/debates/48A3C0A0-19E4-4A7E-AB9E-0F75EAE8B9BB/NorthWalesPoliceAndNicholasChurton?highlight=churton#contribution-155E5433-DFA9-4171-870D-FDE6C9952790|title=North Wales Police and Nicholas Churton - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>. On 12 March 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-03-12/debates/4F8DA548-29D7-4652-99F6-A6BB6C5E0EAE/ProbationReforms?highlight=churton#contribution-EB44FDF8-CB79-4CA6-A6BB-F5DC05664B73|title=Probation Reforms - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and 14 May 2019 there were further mentions about the case in the House of Commons<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2019-05-14/debates/1F4E18A1-F260-4F82-888D-59FEDD63E3C5/PrisonsAndProbation?highlight=churton#contribution-8B2B9B78-B6EF-40D2-A79E-1AE431F64E5E|title=Prisons and Probation - Hansard|website=hansard.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Member of Parliament accusations of being mislead ==\n\nThe IPCC completed a separate investigation into the complaints made by Ian Lucas, the Member of Parliament for Wrexham, that he was misled by  Mark Polin, the Chief Constable of North Wales Police. The IPCC reported that it had found no evidence he had been deliberately misled.<ref name=\":3\" />  In November 2019, Ian Lucas stated that he disagreed with the IPCC findings, and consequently, [[Arfon Jones]], the North Wales [[Police and crime commissioner|Police Crime Commissioner]], said he was \"pursuing a personal vendetta against the former chief constable and impugning his integrity with such distasteful relish\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leaderlive.co.uk/news/18039278.police-boss-ex-wrexham-mp-row-findings-investigation-former-chief-constable/|title=Police boss and ex-Wrexham MP row over findings of investigation into former chief constable|website=The Leader|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/df81f997-1c62-4aeb-92d0-e0063c3d972c?in=17:03:11 House of Commo